I am very sorry to hear of your protracted sexual abuse.  Having had
relationships with victims of sexual assault, and spoken at length
with therapists who treat both victims and the perpetrators of these
crimes, I believe that your problems will persist and grow worse
without prompt and extensive counseling.

To imagine that you can undo the warping influence of a horrific
childhood is to risk all future relationships and happiness for fear
of the work that actually needs to be done.  Your assertions that
you have &quot;grown up&quot;, and that you &quot;refuse to be the victim&quot; are
both wrong and counter-productive.  Childhood trauma often stunts
proper development.  And left untreated, your history will likely
come back to haunt you in all kind of terrible ways.

One of the therapists, who treats sex offenders, has noted the
&quot;uncanny&quot; or &quot;cosmic&quot; coincidence that while a number of her
clients had NO PRIOR HISTORY of sexual deviance, the women
they were married to had been victims of childhood sexual
misconduct.  Do you really want to select or steer your husband /
men towards sexual deviance so that he / they can molest your
children?

Please find a counselor to work on this with, for the sake of your
children if not yourself.

Best of luck,
