The notion that one partner can steer the other into becoming like
the people she knew as a child comes from Dr. Harville Hendrix
in the book &quot;Getting the Love You Want&quot;.  Writing of the Imago, the
mental/emotional image of all of one's childhood care takers, an
associate of Dr. Hendrix noted:

&quot;. . . people either 'pick imago matches, project them, or provoke
them.' &quot;

This is consistent with my own belief that as adults we seek to
reestablish the conditions, situations and circumstances of our
childhood, for any number of reasons.  Most importantly:

1. Having survived childhood under those conditions, we associate
those known conditions and our developed coping skills with survival.

2. Recreating our childhood allows us to again take up former
challenges which had been unresolved.

3. They allow us to recreate ourselves through our children by giving
them the same challenges, hoping that we can get it right this time,
through our younger proxies.

I am aware that this may sound a bit like blaming the victim, but
the &quot;evidence&quot; seems to indicate that they too play a substantial
role in these affairs.

Best regards,
Larry G.
