I understand your desire to absolve the woman of any guilt for
her victimization as a child, and extend that sympathy to
remove any blame for anything she might do as a result, in the
future.  However, I believe that such &quot;politically correct&quot; thinking
may be damaging to others, especially innocent men and
children.  Please understand that if your (commonly expressed)
assertions are in fact wrong, others will suffer.  And I doubt
you would want that kind of guilt on your conscience, would you?

The therapist who made that statement considers herself a &quot;victim
advocate&quot; and has many years of experience in trying to combat
and correct sexual deviance.  I would value her cumulative
experience in such matters much more than I would our idle,
less informed conjectures, preferences and suppositions.

While you are correct in noting that such women may indeed be
selecting partners with a higher potential for sexual deviance, it
should be evident that these women are the factors which transform
that potential into actual sexually criminal behavior.  (As stated
earlier, the sex offender husbands had NO PRIOR HISTORY of
sexual deviance until they married former victims.)

Finally, let us look at how we assign responsibility for crimes and
other wrong-doings.  If a person is abused as a child, or is witness
to abuse, and they grow up and commit or encourage acts of
abuse themselves; are we to hold them blameless for their own
wrongful actions?

The courts (in the U.S.) don't seem to think so.  People are sent
to jail or prison for their actions.  Their past is seldom considered
even a mitigating circumstance.   Now, I for one, would like to
see more effective treatment of offenders, where their pasts can
be explored, and current behavior corrected.  But I would go further
in correcting the people whose counsel, advice or actions encourage
criminal conduct.  That includes CEO's, rap-stars, abusive parents,
wayward sports figures, and unhealed victims.

Just my  opinion.  Your mileage may vary.

Cheers,
